(70, 'Frequently asked questions', '<h3>\n	1- Can I authorise anyone to make the deposit on my behalf?</h3>\n<p>\n	Yes, if you have the corresponding authorisation.</p>\n<p>\n	You must provide this person with written authorisation in which you indicate that you are authorising them to deposit your thesis, attaching your identity document (national ID, residence permit or passport) along with the other documents that we have listed herein. This person must request a prior appointment in order to arrange to make the deposit in your name and must provide their full name.</p>\n<h3>\n	2- What is the minimum period between the thesis being deposited and being read?</h3>\n<p>\n	There are approximately 20 to 60 days between the thesis being deposited and being defended, depending on what time of year it has been deposited.<br />\n	Please check the schedule for deposits in 2017 if the period after you make your deposit includes Christmas, Easter, August or extraordinary periods.</p>\n<h3>\n	3- Do the supervisor and tutor have to make their reports separately?</h3>\n<p>\n	If the candidate is tutored by a supervisor and a tutor, it is acceptable for both of them (supervisor and tutor) to sign the same document.</p>\n<h3>\n	4- What is the composition of the examining board?</h3>\n<p>\n	<strong>Composition:</strong></p>\n<ul>\n	<li>\n		It is mandatory that the president and the 1st substitute of the examining board are professors, tenured professors or &quot;agregats&quot; (also acting official) of the Department of Surgery or the Department of Morphological Sciences of UAB. You can check the department&#39;s professors <a href="Directori.php" target="_blank">here</a>.</li>\n	<li>\n		The other members of the examining board cannot be related to UAB.</li>\n	<li>\n		If you apply for the International Doctor Research Component, at least one expert belonging to a non-Spanish higher education institution or research center with a doctor&#39;s degree (PhD), different from the person responsible during the stay abroad, must be part of the doctoral thesis examining board.</li>\n</ul>\n<p>\n	<strong>Academic status of members of the examining board:</strong></p>\n<ul>\n	<li>\n		If the academic situation of the member of the examining board does not correspond to any of the following (University professor, university college professor, contract professor, tenured university lecturer, tenured university-school lecturer, adjunct lecturer, tenure-track lecturer, retired lecturer, emeritus lecturer, contract PhD lecturer, assistant lecturer on doctoral programmes, researcher, research lecturer or tenured researcher at the CSIC, tenured scientist at the CSIC, researcher at the ICREA, researcher at the Ram&oacute;n y Cajal University), a CV must provided from the examining board member where the research projects and the publications must be indicated for the past five years.</li>\n	<li>\n		Of all those members of the examining board who are not university professors and neither are doctors by the UAB, a copy of its title of doctor must be brought.</li>\n	<li>\n		Directors, ex-directors, tutors, ex-tutors during the stay abroad (International Doctoral Research Component) or co-authors of the articles included in the thesis cannot be part of the examining board.</li>\n</ul>\n<h3>\n	5- What is mandatory on the thesis presentation?</h3>\n<p>\n	As a general rule, the general criteria that you can consult <a href="http://www.uab.cat/doc/criterios_formales_ejemplares_tesis.pdf" target="_blank">here</a> should be followed.</p>\n<p>\n	On the cover it is mandatory to appear &#39;thesis&#39; and the title of the thesis, author, supervisors, tutor, Doctoral Programme in Surgery and Morphological Sciences, Department of Surgery or Department of Morphological Sciences, UAB and year.</p>\n<h3>\n	6- Does the thesis deposit have an expiry date?</h3>\n<p>\n	If you do not defend your thesis within 3 months from the date of deposit, you will have to formally deposit the thesis again, along with appointment of the examining board, etc. and pay again the corresponding thesis deposit and tutorial fees&nbsp; if a new academic year has started.</p>\n<h3>\n	7- TDX and postponing the thesis</h3>\n<p>\n	Pursuant to RD 99/2011, all theses deposited as from 13/02/2012 must be published on the TDX. However, a system has been put in place to safeguard the subsequent publication of theses in science journals or publications. If this is your case, on making the deposit you can request for the thesis to be kept on hold for between 6 and 24 months, depending on the different scenarios described in the acceptance document for digitising the thesis (downloadable here). You will need to submit a favourable report from the thesis supervisor(s) explaining the reasons for the delay.</p>\n<h3>\n	8- How is the doctoral thesis graded?</h3>\n<p>\n	In application of Transitory Disposition One on &quot;candidates in conformity with the previous orders&quot;, in Royal Decree 99/2011, of January 28, regulating official doctorate programmes, the examining board for doctoral theses deposited at the School for Doctoral Studies from 13/02/2012 issues a report with the overall grade awarded to the thesis, expressed as &quot;no apte&quot; (D), &quot;aprovat&quot; (C), &quot;notable&quot; (B) or &quot;excel&bull;lent&quot; (A). If the grade is &ldquo;excel&middot;lent&rdquo;, the same examining board may meet once more to propose that the doctoral thesis be awarded a cum laude distinction, for which a secret ballot must be taken and the decision to propose the distinction must be unanimous.</p>\n', 107, '', 5, 2),
